// TEST: exec_py_loop_tail_println_all_iterations
// EXPECT: output "1;2;3;4;5;done"
// EXPECT: targets python
//
// A `for`-loop body whose TAIL is a side-effecting call (`print(...)`) must run
// on EVERY iteration. The Python backend's shared `emit_block_body` had treated
// a block tail as a function-body `return`, so the loop body lowered to
// `for i in …: return print(...)` — the `return` aborts `main` after the FIRST
// iteration. fizzbuzz printed one line; inventory-system listed one product;
// both still exited 0, so the exec audit's exit-code-only view hid it.
//
// The py fix routes loop bodies through `emit_loop_body`, which sets a
// statement-position discard flag so a loop-body tail expression is emitted as a
// bare statement (`print(...)`) — not `return print(...)`. The trailing
// `print("done")` after the loop proves control did NOT leave `main` early.
//
// PYTHON-ONLY: this fixture pins the Python loop-tail lowering specifically
// (the JS/TS truncation is fixed separately, #240 for TS). A separate `py_*`
// fixture name keeps it from claiming cross-backend coverage it does not assert.
//
// `main` is intentionally NOT `public` (see hello_world.bock for the Go
// entry-point rationale).
module main

fn main() -> Void {
  for i in 1..=5 {
    print("${i};")
  }
  print("done")
}
